            },
            "answer_text": "people sure want you to think so. but their not. people are however great noticers of differences in all things, not just people. but people are probably the most widely noticed. ive studied race and identity in a class in college.i disagree with much of what was presented because it was presented as \u201cwhitemen are the cause of all the worlds problems\u201d kind of bias. in addition to being wired to notice differences. we are wired to notice patterns of behavior. when bad things happen we try to make sense of them, and its easy to see how people could associate things with certain peoples based on a limited sample. but overall humans have a mistrust of what i call \u201coutsiders\u201d: people different than a main group. This idea can be proven by looking at natural populations of animals. take chimps for example: they war with \u201coutsiders\u201d because they mean to take resources from them. the first law of economics is that there is never enough to go around. outsiders have to realize that they are outsiders and do everything in their power to convince the main group that they deserve to be considered part of the main group. this is on an individual level, not on a group level\u2026despite current politics and ridiculous identity sciences. the individual must become part of the whole in the best most efficient way possible or the main group will not trust the outsider. our current society thinks that all people ought to be smart enough to understand that my theory above is crap and that people are supposed to just accept everyone and everything as is. this is just not how nature works. this is not how trust works, by blind faith in people. once bitten twice shy. of course the politicians and race baiters will never allow anyone to believe my theory because they would lose control over people. the real way to become one people is to accept the idea that you cannot go against the grain and make friends. you go a tiny bit, as much as the main group allows but thats it. when my great grandparents came from italy they told my dad \u201cto speak english because we are american now. italy had nothing for us\u201d they adopted american celebrations and customs and were happy. sure no one wants to lose what they know, but ask yourself why you came here or moved to this neighborhood for. was it to force everyone to accept you or to be more like them? because no one is going to let you change them as a group. youll be run out of town. ",
