                "name": "Vince Parker",
                "href": "/profile/Vince-Parker"
            },
            "answer_text": "Anyone can be a racist, or not.  Anyone can have 'bad' thoughts, or not.  And anyone can do 'bad' things, or not.   So if we don't like the 'bad' things, we can always find love, which is a good thing.  And anyone can have 'love', or not.   So we are all both bad, and good.  And we can all learn to focus on the good parts.   Like when I am the subject of a racist remark, or racial discrimination, I tend not to be offended at all.  In fact the experience makes me smile inside.  Because I love them.  And that is what matters to me.  I am glad they are there and a part of my life experience.  You know, but if they are chasing me or trying to hurt me, I'm not just goin' to stand there like an idiot;  I will protect myself.  But it will be of necessity and out of love, much like the necessity for me to kill an animal or plant in order for me to survive.  I do it with respect for life. So when I see 'racism' in the world, all I see are other humans; some whom have chosen to put more energy in racist activities, and others who choose to be either bothered by it or not.   Not being bothered by racism, I think, allows one to put more focus on making positive changes in the areas where people ought to get along better.  Not being 'bothered' by something does not mean you don't care, but rather it means you care more, for both parties.  Being 'bothered' puts more weight on one side.   Of course, putting a group of 'bothered' people together to combat another group is also a form of 'balancing' and justification for adding 'weight'.  That's probably why we have wars, to balance things out.  I'm trying to say that being 'bothered' by something is fine too.   So bottom line is that we are all basically nice people (because we are all part of the same love) who sometimes may not seem too nice, depending on who's shoes we happen to be standing in. ",
