                "name": "Bobby Nazari",
                "href": "/profile/Bobby-Nazari"
            },
            "answer_text": "I don\u2019t believe so, but I do believe that society tends to shape us to be that way. I\u2019m a Muslim and when I was growing up my family always told me to be careful of x because \u201cx people were dangerous.\u201d Nowadays, whenever I see a x person I don\u2019t feel slightly on edge or uncomfortable because my parents and grandparents always were uncomfortable around them and I didn\u2019t want to behave like my parents or grandparents. It\u2019s up to new generations to stop any racism that is being passed down the bloodlines, because it is evident. I don\u2019t look like the stereotypical Muslim so when people realize I am, some don\u2019t change, but some act different. For example, in history class the teacher asked a question about Muslims and I answered and when the teacher asked how I knew, I said it was because I was a Muslim. The teacher kind of looked surprised and acted normal, but some kid at my table stiffened and began looking at me differently ever since. Often times, it seems to be that certain ethnicities that experience racism towards themselved, don\u2019t reciprocate the behavior because they know how it hurts and it\u2019s a behavior that can be controlled. Now please remember that all this is my opinion and experience, so it might be different for you or someone else. TL/DR: No. ",
