                "href": "/profile/Marcus-Geduld"
            },
            "answer_text": "Humans are inherently tribal. We are biased towards people we feel are like us and against outsiders. What constitutes an outsider differs from person to person. It often coincides at least partly with race, because \"looks different from me\" is such a clear sign. But for an individual person, race might not matter as much as other things.  I'm a white New Yorker. I feel more comfortable around black New Yorkers than white rural people. That's still tribalism. It just happens not to be based on skin color. ",
