            "answer_text": "Humans, like many other animals, are wired to gravitate toward those that look the same as they do. People are comfortable with what is familiar to them. In addition, people of the same ethnicity may have more in common than their appearance. They may eat the same foods, wear the same clothes and speak the same language. All of this creates a comfort zone. When a person sees someone who looks different and acts differently, it may create discomfort. That, in and of itself, isn't racism. Racism is when someone treats someone else differently because of race. People may do this without even realizing it. If a person is uncomfortable and doesn't address a person who has entered the store, that may be racist. Did every other person get spoken to upon entering? This is why people get angry. People must be treated equation public establishments. ",
